# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hipaa-compliance
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] In the context of medical data, anonymized data refers to data from which the patient cannot be identified by the recipient of the information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] The name, address, and full postcode must be removed, together with any other information which, in conjunction with other data held by or disclosed to the recipient, could identify the patient.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] There will always be a risk that anonymized data may not stay anonymous over time.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] Pairing the anonymized dataset with other data, clever techniques and raw power are some of the ways previously anonymous data sets have become de-anonymized; The data subjects are no longer anonymous.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] De-anonymization is the reverse process in which anonymous data is cross-referenced with other data sources to re-identify the anonymous data source.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] Generalization and perturbation are the two popular anonymization approaches for relational data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] The process of obscuring data with the ability to re-identify it later is also called pseudonymization and is one way companies can store data in a way that is HIPAA compliant.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] However, according to ARTICLE 29 DATA PROTECTION WORKING PARTY, Directive 95/46/EC refers to anonymisation in Recital 26 "signifies that to anonymise any data, the data must be stripped of sufficient elements such that the data subject can no longer be identified.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] More precisely, that data must be processed in such a way that it can no longer be used to identify a natural person by using “all the means likely reasonably to be used” by either the controller or a third party.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] An important factor is that the processing must be irreversible.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] The Directive does not clarify how such a de-identification process should or could be performed.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] The focus is on the outcome: that data should be such as not to allow the data subject to be identified via “all” “likely” and “reasonable” means.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] Reference is made to codes of conduct as a tool to set out possible anonymisation mechanisms as well as retention in a form in which identification of the data subject is “no longer possible”.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] There are five types of data anonymization operations: generalization, suppression, anatomization, permutation, and perturbation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) requires that stored data on people in the EU undergo either anonymization or a pseudonymization process.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] According to the EDPS and AEPD, no one, including the data controller, should be able to re-identify data subjects in a properly anonymized dataset.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] Research by data scientists at Imperial College in London and UCLouvain in Belgium, as well as a ruling by Judge Michal Agmon-Gonen of the Tel Aviv District Court, highlight the shortcomings of "Anonymisation" in today's big data world.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] Anonymisation reflects an outdated approach to data protection that was developed when the processing of data was limited to isolated (siloed) applications, prior to the popularity of big data processing involving the widespread sharing and combining of data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] Removing identifying metadata from computer files is important for anonymizing them.
[src:hipaa-compliance/data-anonymization] Metadata removal tools are useful for achieving this.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The **Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996** (**HIPAA** or the **Kennedy–Kassebaum Act**) is a United States Act of Congress enacted by the 104th United States Congress and signed into law by President Bill Clinton on August 21, 1996.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] It aimed to alter the transfer of healthcare information and stipulated guidelines by which personally identifiable information maintained by the healthcare and healthcare insurance industries should be protected from fraud and theft, and addressed some limitations on healthcare insurance coverage.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] It generally prohibits healthcare providers and businesses called covered entities from disclosing protected information to anyone other than a patient and the patient's authorized representatives without their consent.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The law does not restrict patients from accessing their own information, except in limited cases.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Furthermore, it does not prohibit patients from voluntarily sharing their health information however they choose, nor does it require confidentiality where a patient discloses medical information to family members, friends, or other individuals not employees of a covered entity.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Title II, known as the Administrative Simplification (AS) provisions, requires the establishment of national standards for electronic health care transactions and national identifiers for providers, health insurance plans, and employers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Title III sets guidelines for pre-tax medical spending accounts.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Title IV sets guidelines for group health plans.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Title V governs company-owned life insurance policies.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] There are five sections to the act, known as titles.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Title I of HIPAA regulates the availability and breadth of group health plans and certain individual health insurance policies.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] It amended the Employee Retirement Income Security Act, the Public Health Service Act, and the Internal Revenue Code.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Title I also addresses the issue of "job lock," where employees remain in a job to avoid losing health coverage.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] To combat the job lock issue, the Title protects health insurance coverage for workers and their families if they lose or change their jobs.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Title I requires the coverage of and limits restrictions that a group health plan can place on benefits for preexisting conditions.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Group health plans may refuse to provide benefits in relation to preexisting conditions for either 12 months following enrollment in the plan or 18 months in the case of late enrollment.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Title I allows individuals to reduce the exclusion period by the amount of time they have had "creditable coverage" before enrolling in the plan and after any "significant breaks" in coverage.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] "Creditable coverage" includes nearly all group and individual health plans, Medicare, and Medicaid.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] A "significant break" in coverage is defined as any 63-day period without any creditable coverage.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Along with an exception, it allows employers to tie premiums or co-payments to tobacco use or body mass index (BMI).
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Some health care plans are exempted from Title I requirements, such as long-term health plans and limited-scope plans like dental or vision plans offered separately from the general health plan.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] However, if such benefits are part of the general health plan, then HIPAA still applies to such benefits.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] For example, if the new plan offers dental benefits, then creditable continuous coverage under the old health plan must be counted towards any of its exclusion periods for dental benefits.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] An alternate method of calculating creditable continuous coverage is available to the health plan under Title I.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] 5 categories of health coverage can be considered separately, including dental and vision coverage.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Hidden exclusion periods are invalid under Title I.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] For example: ‘The accident must have occurred while the beneficiary was covered under this same health insurance contract.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Such clauses must not be acted upon by the health plan.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Also, they must be re-written to comply with HIPAA.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Title II of HIPAA establishes policies and procedures for maintaining the privacy and the security of individually identifiable health information, outlines numerous offenses relating to health care, and establishes civil and criminal penalties for violations.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] It also creates several programs to control fraud and abuse within the health care system.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The most significant provisions of Title II are the Administrative Simplification rules.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Title II requires the Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) to increase the efficiency of the health-care system by creating standards for the use and dissemination of health care information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] These rules apply to "covered entities" as defined by HIPAA and the HHS.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Covered entities include health plans, health care clearinghouses (e.g., billing services and community health information systems), and health care providers that transmit health care data in a way regulated by HIPAA.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Per the requirements of Title II, the HHS has promulgated five rules regarding Administrative Simplification: the Privacy Rule, the Transactions and Code Sets Rule, the Security Rule, the Unique Identifiers Rule, and the Enforcement Rule.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The Privacy Rule came into effect on April 14, 2003, with a one-year extension for certain "small plans".
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] By regulation, the HHS extended the HIPAA privacy rule to independent contractors of covered entities who fit within the definition of "business associates".
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] PHI is any information that is held by a covered entity regarding health status, provision of health care, or health care payment that can be linked to any individual.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] This includes any part of an individual's medical record or payment history.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Covered entities must disclose PHI to the individual within 30 days upon request.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] They must also disclose PHI when required to do so by law, such as reporting suspected child abuse to state child welfare agencies.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] A covered entity may disclose PHI to certain parties to facilitate treatment, payment, or health care operations without a patient's express written authorization.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Any other disclosures of PHI require the covered entity to obtain written authorization from the individual for disclosure.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] In any case, when a covered entity discloses any PHI, it must make a reasonable effort to disclose only the minimum necessary information required to achieve its purpose.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The Privacy Rule gives individuals the right to request that a covered entity correct any inaccurate PHI.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] It also requires covered entities to take reasonable steps on ensuring the confidentiality of communications with individuals.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] For example, an individual can ask to be called at their work number instead of home or cell phone numbers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The Privacy Rule requires covered entities to notify individuals of the use of their PHI.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Covered entities must also keep track of disclosures of PHI and document privacy policies and procedures.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] They must appoint a Privacy Official and a contact person responsible for receiving complaints and train all members of their workforce in procedures regarding PHI.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Individuals who believe that the Privacy Rule is not being upheld can file a complaint with the Department of Health and Human Services Office for Civil Rights (OCR).
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] In 2006, the *Wall Street Journal* reported that the OCR had a long backlog and ignored most complaints.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] "Complaints of privacy violations have been piling up at the Department of Health and Human Services.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Between April of 2003 and November 2006, the agency fielded 23,886 complaints related to medical-privacy rules, but it has not yet taken any enforcement actions against hospitals, doctors, insurers or anyone else for rule violations.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] An HHS Office for Civil Rights investigation showed that from 2005 to 2008, unauthorized employees repeatedly and without legitimate cause looked at the electronic protected health information of numerous UCLAHS patients.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] It is a misconception that the Privacy Rule creates a right for any individual to refuse to disclose any health information (such as chronic conditions or immunization records) if requested by an employer or business.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] In January 2013, HIPAA was updated via the Final Omnibus Rule.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The updates included changes to the Security Rule and Breach Notification portions of the HITECH Act.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The most significant changes related to the expansion of requirements to include business associates, where only covered entities had originally been held to uphold these sections of the law.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] In addition, the definition of "significant harm" to an individual in the analysis of a breach was updated to provide more scrutiny to covered entities with the intent of disclosing unreported breaches.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Previously, an organization needed proof that harm had occurred, whereas now organizations must prove that harm had not occurred.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Protection of PHI was changed from indefinite to 50 years after death.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] More severe penalties for violation of PHI privacy requirements were also approved.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The HIPAA Privacy rule may be waived during disasters.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Limited waivers have been issued in cases such as Hurricane Harvey in 2017.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] See the Privacy section of the Health Information Technology for Economic and Clinical Health Act (HITECH Act).
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The Privacy Rule requires medical providers to give individuals access to their PHI.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] After an individual requests information in writing (typically using the provider's form for this purpose), a provider has up to 30 days to provide a copy of the information to the individual.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] An individual may request the information in electronic form or hard copy, and the provider is obligated to attempt to conform to the requested format.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] For providers using an electronic health record (EHR) system that is certified using CEHRT (Certified Electronic Health Record Technology) criteria, individuals must be allowed to obtain the PHI in electronic form.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Providers are encouraged to provide the information expediently, especially in the case of electronic record requests.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Individuals have the broad right to access their health-related information, including medical records, notes, images, lab results, and insurance and billing information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Explicitly excluded are the private psychotherapy notes of a provider and information gathered by a provider to defend against a lawsuit.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Providers can charge a reasonable amount related to the cost of providing the copy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] However, no charge is allowable when providing data electronically from a certified EHR using the "view, download, and transfer" feature required for certification.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] When using unencrypted email, the individual must understand and accept the risks to privacy using this technology (the information may be intercepted and examined by others).
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Regardless of delivery technology, a provider must continue to fully secure the PHI while in their system and can deny the delivery method if it poses additional risk to PHI while in their system.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] An individual may also request (in writing) that their PHI be delivered to a designated third party such as a family care provider or service used to collect or manage their records, such as a Personal Health Record application.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] For example, a patient can request in writing that her ob-gyn provider digitally transmit records of her latest prenatal visit to a pregnancy self-care app that she has on her mobile phone.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] According to their interpretations of HIPAA, hospitals will not reveal information over the phone to relatives of admitted patients.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] This has, in some instances, impeded the location of missing persons.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] After the Asiana Airlines Flight 214 San Francisco crash, some hospitals were reluctant to disclose the identities of passengers that they were treating, making it difficult for Asiana and the relatives to locate them.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] In one instance, a man in Washington state was unable to obtain information about his injured mother.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Janlori Goldman, director of the advocacy group Health Privacy Project, said that some hospitals are being "overcautious" and misapplying the law, as reported by The New York Times.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Suburban Hospital in Bethesda, Md., interpreted a federal regulation that requires hospitals to allow patients to opt out of being included in the hospital directory as meaning that patients want to be kept out of the directory unless they specifically say otherwise.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] As a result, if a patient is unconscious or otherwise unable to choose to be included in the directory, relatives and friends might not be able to find them, Goldman said.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] HIPAA was intended to make health care in the United States more efficient by standardizing health care transactions.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] To this end, HIPAA added a new Part C titled "Administrative Simplification" to Title XI of the Social Security Act, requiring all health plans to engage in health care transactions in a standardized way.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The HIPAA/EDI (electronic data interchange) provision was scheduled to take effect from October 16, 2003, with a one-year extension for certain "small plans".
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] However, due to widespread confusion and difficulty in implementing the rule, Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS) granted a one-year extension to all parties.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] On January 1, 2012, newer versions, ASC X12 005010 and NCPDP D.0 came into effect, replacing the previous ASC X12 004010 and NCPDP 5.1 mandate.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The ASC X12 005010 version provides a mechanism allowing the use of ICD-10-CM as well as other improvements.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] HIPAA-covered health plans are now required to use standardized HIPAA electronic transactions (see 42 USC § 1320d-2 and 45 CFR Part 162).
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Information about this can be found in the final rule for HIPAA electronic transaction standards (74 Fed.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] 3296, published in the Federal Register on January 16, 2009), and on the CMS website.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The **EDI Health Care Claim Transaction Set** (837) is used to submit health care claim billing information, encounter information, or both, except for retail pharmacy claims (see EDI Retail Pharmacy Claim Transaction).
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] It can be sent from providers of health care services to payers, either directly or via intermediary billers and claims clearinghouses.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] For example, a state mental health agency may mandate all health care claims, providers and health plans who trade professional (medical) health care claims electronically must use the 837 Health Care Claim professional standard to send in claims.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] As there are many different business applications for the health care claim, there can be slight derivations to cover specific institutions, professionals, chiropractors, dentists, etc.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The **EDI Benefit Enrollment and Maintenance Set** (834) can be used by employers, unions, government agencies, associations, or insurance agencies to enroll members to a payer.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The payer is a healthcare organization that pays claims, administers insurance, or offers a benefit or product.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Examples of payers include an insurance company, healthcare professional (HMO), preferred provider organization (PPO), government agency (Medicaid, Medicare etc.) or any organization that may be contracted by one of these former groups.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The size of many fields {segment elements} will be expanded, causing a need for all IT providers to expand corresponding fields, elements, files, GUI, paper media, and databases.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Some segments have been removed from existing Transaction Sets.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Many segments have been added to existing Transaction Sets, allowing greater tracking and reporting of cost and patient encounters.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Capacity to use both "International Classification of Diseases" versions 9 (ICD-9) and 10 (ICD-10-CM) has been added.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The Final Rule on Security Standards was issued on February 20, 2003.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The Security Rule complements the Privacy Rule.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] While the Privacy Rule pertains to all Protected Health Information (PHI) including paper and electronic, the Security Rule deals specifically with Electronic Protected Health Information (EPHI).
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] It outlines three types of security safeguards required for compliance: administrative, physical, and technical.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] For each of these types, the Rule identifies various security standards, and for each standard, it names both required and addressable implementation specifications.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Required specifications must be adopted and administered as dictated by the Rule.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Addressable specifications are more flexible.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Individual covered entities can evaluate their own situation and determine the best way to implement addressable specifications.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Some privacy advocates have argued that this "flexibility" may provide too much latitude to covered entities.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Software tools have been developed to assist covered entities in the risk analysis and remediation tracking.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] HIPAA replaced various identifiers used by health plans, Medicare, Medicaid, and other government programs with an NPI.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The NPI is unique and national, never re-used, and except for institutions, a provider usually can have only one.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] However, the NPI does not replace a provider's DEA number, state license number, or tax identification number.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The NPI is 10 digits (may be alphanumeric), with the last digit being a checksum.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The NPI cannot contain any embedded intelligence; in other words, the NPI is simply a number that does not itself have any additional meaning.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] An institution may obtain multiple NPIs for different "sub-parts" such as a free-standing cancer center or rehab facility.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] On February 16, 2006, HHS issued the Final Rule regarding HIPAA enforcement.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The Enforcement Rule sets civil money penalties for violating HIPAA rules and establishes procedures for investigations and hearings for HIPAA violations.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] For many years there were few prosecutions for violations.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] As of March 2013, the United States Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) has investigated over 19,306 cases that have been resolved by requiring changes in privacy practice or by corrective action.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] If HHS determines noncompliance, entities must apply corrective measures.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Complaints have been investigated against many different types of businesses, such as national pharmacy chains, major health care centers, insurance groups, hospital chains, and other small providers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] There were 9,146 cases where the HHS investigation found that HIPAA was followed correctly.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] There were 44,118 cases that HHS did not find eligible cause for enforcement; for example, a violation that started before HIPAA started, cases withdrawn by the pursuer, or an activity that does not actually violate the Rules.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Title III standardizes the amount that may be saved per person in a pre-tax medical savings account.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Beginning in 1997, a medical savings account ("MSA") became available to employees covered under an employer-sponsored high deductible plan, these being small employer and self-employed individuals.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Title IV specifies conditions for group health plans regarding coverage of persons with preexisting conditions, and modifies continuation of coverage requirements.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] It also clarifies continuation coverage requirements and includes COBRA clarification.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Title V includes provisions related to company-owned life insurance for employers providing company-owned life insurance premiums, prohibiting the tax deduction of interest on life insurance loans, company endowments, or contracts related to the company.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] It also repeals the financial institution rule to interest allocation rules.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The enactment of the Privacy and Security Rules caused major changes to how physicians and medical centers operate.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The complex legalities and potentially stiff penalties associated with HIPAA, as well as the increase in paperwork and the cost of its implementation, were causes for concern among physicians and medical centers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] An August 2006 article in the journal *Annals of Internal Medicine* detailed some such concerns over the implementation and effects of HIPAA.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] HIPAA restrictions on researchers have affected their ability to perform retrospective, chart-based research as well as their ability to prospectively evaluate patients by contacting them for follow-up.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] A study from the University of Michigan demonstrated that implementation of the HIPAA Privacy rule resulted in a drop from 96% to 34% in the proportion of follow-up surveys completed by study patients being followed after a heart attack.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Another study, detailing the effects of HIPAA on recruitment for a study on cancer prevention, demonstrated that HIPAA-mandated changes led to a 73% decrease in patient accrual, a tripling of time spent recruiting patients, and a tripling of mean recruitment costs.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Under HIPAA, informed consent forms for research studies must document how protected health information will be kept private, potentially increasing barriers to participation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] These data suggest that HIPAA privacy rules may have negative effects on the cost and quality of medical research.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Kim Eagle, professor of internal medicine at the University of Michigan, was quoted in the *Annals* article as saying, "Privacy is important, but research is also important for improving care.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The complexity of HIPAA, combined with potentially stiff penalties for violators, can lead physicians and medical centers to withhold information from those who may have a right to it.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] A review of the implementation of the HIPAA Privacy Rule by the U.S.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Government Accountability Office found that health care providers were "uncertain about their legal privacy responsibilities and often responded with an overly guarded approach to disclosing information ... than necessary to ensure compliance with the Privacy rule".
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Standardizing the handling and sharing of health information under HIPAA has contributed to a decrease in medical errors.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Accurate and timely access to patient information ensures that healthcare providers make informed decisions, reducing the risk of errors related to incomplete or incorrect data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] This standardization supports safer clinical practices and better patient outcomes.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Furthermore, HIPAA grants patients the right to access their own health information, request amendments to their records, and obtain an accounting of disclosures.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] This empowers patients to be more involved in their healthcare decisions and ensures transparency in the handling of their information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] In the period immediately before the enactment of the HIPAA Privacy and Security Acts, medical centers and medical practices were charged with complying with the new requirements.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Many practices and centers turned to private consultants for compliance assistance.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Education and training of healthcare providers is a requirement for correct implementation of both the HIPAA Privacy Rule and Security Rule.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Healthcare providers must receive initial training on HIPAA policies and procedures, including the Privacy Rule and the Security Rule.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] This training covers how to handle protected health information (PHI), patient rights, and the minimum necessary standard.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Providers learn about the types of information that are protected under HIPAA, such as medical records, billing information and any other health information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] They are also taught about patients' rights under HIPAA, such as the right to access their health records and request correction.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Regular fresher training is recommended to keep healthcare providers up to date with any changes in HIPAA regulations and best practices.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] This includes updates on new policies, procedures, and any material changes to existing practices.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The *HIPPA* misspelling has been observed among COVID-19 scammers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Department of Health and Human Services Office for Civil Rights, between April 2003 and January 2013, it received 91,000 complaints of HIPAA violations, in which 22,000 led to enforcement actions of varying kinds (from settlements to fines) and 521 led to referrals to the U.S.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Department of Justice as criminal actions.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] According to Koczkodaj et al., 2018, the total number of individuals affected since October 2009 is 173,398,820.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] In 1994, President Clinton expressed his goals to improve the healthcare system.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] However, his reforms did not succeed, most likely due to a lack of support.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] The Congressional Quarterly Almanac of 1996 explains how two senators, Nancy Kassebaum (R-KS) and Ted Kennedy (D-MA) came together and created a bill called the Health Insurance Reform Act of 1995, more commonly known as the Kassebaum-Kennedy Bill.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] This bill was stalled despite making it out of the Senate.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] In the 1996 State of the Union address, Clinton pressed the issue, and it resulted in bipartisan cooperation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] After much debate and negotiation, there was a shift in momentum once a compromise between Kennedy and Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer was accepted following alterations to the original Kassebaum-Kennedy Bill.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] Soon after this, the bill was signed into law by President Clinton and was named the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996 (HIPAA).
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] On 25 June 2024, the Department of Health and Human Services issued a new rule to "support reproductive health care privacy." The rule modifies the Standards for Privacy of Individually Identifiable Health Information under HIPAA and the HITECH Act.
[src:hipaa-compliance/health-insurance-portability-and-accountability-act] One aspect of this new change prohibits health officials from divulging records related to reproductive health such as fertility, contraceptive usage, and miscarriages, to law enforcement unless for a criminal investigation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Various types of personal information often come under privacy concerns.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Privacy concerns exist wherever personally identifiable information or other sensitive information is collected, stored, used, and finally destroyed or deleted – in digital form or otherwise.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Improper or non-existent disclosure control can be the root cause for privacy issues.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Informed consent mechanisms including privacy policies and dynamic consent are important in communicating to data subjects the different uses of their personally identifiable information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Warren II and Louis Brandeis published "The Right to Privacy", an article explaining "the right to be let alone," which helped establish a right to privacy in the United States.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Their guidelines set the foundation for how privacy can be understood in terms of personal data, and influenced the development of the privacy laws of the United States.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In the United States, the Privacy Act of 1974 represented an achievement in information privacy law.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The law set a Code of Fair Information Practice to govern how federal agencies collect personal information and data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] After the Watergate and COINTELPRO scandals involving illegal government use of surveillance, this privacy law was intended to help restore public trust in the government.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The Act allowed a person to have the right to access information about themselves and know how their information would be used.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The growth of the internet's popularity in the early 2000s presented different privacy concerns as many companies and organizations began to collect user's personal data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Scholars such as Daniel Solove explained the importance of informed consent.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In 2018, the Facebook–Cambridge Analytica data scandal introduced new privacy risks to the public.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] A consulting firm called Cambridge Analytica collected personal user data from over 85 million Facebook users without informed consent.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The data collected was used to assist in politically targeted ads during the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] This resulted in the United States Federal Trade Commission fining Facebook $5 billion.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The Cambridge Analytica scandal influenced new legislation such as the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Information about a person's financial transactions, including the amount of assets, positions held in stocks or funds, outstanding debts, and purchases can be sensitive.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] If criminals gain access to information such as a person's accounts or credit card numbers, that person could become the victim of fraud or identity theft.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Information about a person's purchases can reveal a great deal about that person's history, such as places they have visited, whom they have contact with, products they have used, their activities and habits, or medications they have used.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In some cases, corporations may use this information to target individuals with marketing customized towards those individual's personal preferences, which that person may or may not approve.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The ability to control the information one reveals about oneself over the internet and who can access that information has become a growing concern.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] These concerns include whether email can be stored or read by third parties without consent or whether third parties can continue to track the websites that someone visited.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Another concern is whether websites one visits can collect, store, and possibly share personally identifiable information about users.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The advent of various search engines and the use of data mining created a capability for data about individuals to be collected and combined from a wide variety of sources very easily.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] AI facilitated creating inferential information about individuals and groups based on such enormous amounts of collected data, transforming the information economy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The FTC has provided a set of guidelines that represent widely accepted concepts concerning fair information practices in an electronic marketplace, called the Fair Information Practice Principles.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] But these have been critiqued for their insufficiency in the context of AI-enabled inferential information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The same applies to any kind of traffic generated on the Internet, including web browsing, instant messaging, and others.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In order not to give away too much personal information, emails can be encrypted and browsing of webpages as well as other online activities can be done anonymously via anonymizers, or by open source distributed anonymizers, so-called mix networks.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Nym and I2P are examples of well-known mix nets.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] With social media and e-commerce sites being used more frequently, there are more potential openings for stealing consumer's data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Companies can see which types of products consumers like to purchase and can use targeted ads to try to make people purchase more items thinking that this is what they will want to purchase.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] However, sometimes this type of data is used without explicit consent.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Users are unaware of all of the personal information that is collected about them.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Cookies track browsing data and location settings show where a person is based out of, and can show shops or products that are physically located near someone.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] These combined that be a big safety and privacy issue for users if their data is not being stored safely.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] With laws like the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA), people's data can be protected and they asked for explicit consent before using said data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Globally, many nations are trying to implement similar clauses to protect consumers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Email is not the only internet content with privacy concerns.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In an age where increasing amounts of information are online, social networking sites pose additional privacy challenges.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] People may be tagged in photos or have valuable information exposed about themselves either by choice or unexpectedly by others, referred to as participatory surveillance.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Data about location can also be accidentally published, for example, when someone posts a picture with a store as a background.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Caution should be exercised when posting information online.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Social networks vary in what they allow users to make private and what remains publicly accessible.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Without strong security settings in place and careful attention to what remains public, a person can be profiled by searching for and collecting disparate pieces of information, leading to cases of cyberstalking or reputation damage.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Cookies are used on websites so that users may allow the website to retrieve some information from the user's internet, but they usually do not mention what the data being retrieved is.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In 2018, the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) passed a regulation that forces websites to visibly disclose to consumers their information privacy practices, referred to as cookie notices.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] This was issued to give consumers the choice of what information about their behavior they consent to letting websites track; however, its effectiveness is controversial.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Some websites may engage in deceptive practices such as placing cookie notices in places on the page that are not visible or only giving consumers notice that their information is being tracked but not allowing them to change their privacy settings.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Apps like Instagram and Facebook collect user data for a personalized app experience; however, they track user activity on other apps, which jeopardizes users' privacy and data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] By controlling how visible these cookie notices are, companies can discreetly collect data, giving them more power over consumers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In the United Kingdom in 2012, the Education Secretary Michael Gove described the National Pupil Database as a "rich dataset" whose value could be "maximised" by making it more openly accessible, including to private companies.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] An example of a data request that Gove indicated had been rejected in the past, but might be possible under an improved version of privacy regulations, was for "analysis on sexual exploitation".
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] This describes the ability to control what information one reveals about oneself over cable television, and who can access that information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] For example, third parties can track IP TV programs someone has watched at any given time.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Within academia, Institutional Review Boards function to assure that adequate measures are taken to ensure both the privacy and confidentiality of human subjects in research.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] When an individual or group of people steal consumer's data it is considered a breach of data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] It is a common threat to one's information privacy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] This includes information such as names, date of birth, credit card information, and social security numbers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] These types of data breaches can happen when companies do not have the most current or secure infrastructure to secure and encrypt data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] A small gap can open data to being leaked from outsiders.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] It should also be noted that breaches can happen from inside employees exposing information too.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Companies are investing time in teaching about suspicious activity and using multi factor authentication systems.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] On a federal level in Europe, governments are now mandating that companies report breaches in a timely manner.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In America HIPAA functions in a similar way and notifies patients when data has been exposed With types of guidelines in place, companies and countries are working to protect personal information and explain how personal data can and should be used.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Laws surrounding information privacy are important for protecting information globally.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] This includes laws that ensure data is collected with consent and is used with transparency .
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In the continent of Europe, a guideline called The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation requires everyone to ask for consent before using consumer data and to limit the amount of data companies need to take from users in general.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation has shown success, and has prompted other nations to follow suit.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] For example, the state of California and the country of Canada decided to create and implement their own version of the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] California created the California Privacy Rights Act (CPRA, 2020) and Canada created the PIPEDA (Government of Canada, 2021), both modeling their guidelines on The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation that puts consumer and user data and privacy right's first.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] More broadly, the U.S. collectively is still working on creating a comprehensive program that can protect data within the many sectors of jobs and companies operating out of the U.S.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] However, there are smaller guidelines and policies for each organization.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] For example, HIPAA or Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act protects medical patient data and information This is not on a national level that protects all user data from different types of companies, but in the U.S. there are organization and industry level protections created.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Artificial intelligence can be seen as a hindrance to protecting information privacy as they collect data widely.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] According to the International Association of Privacy Professionals, about 68% of consumers globally express concern about their privacy online with 57% agreeing that AI can be a threat to their data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] These concerns have intensified as generative AI tools, which learn from data scraped from the web, have become more widely adopted.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] AI privacy concerns can be linked to unregulated data collection methods, opaque algorithms, and data persistence.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Algorithmic opacity means not understanding exactly how and where AI is getting their data and sources from..
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The lack of clear visibility can make it difficult for someone to understand how their information is being found and used.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Data persistence is data existing for an extended period of time online that can also be without consent.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] As of now in the United States there are not any explicit federal laws governing AI in terms of data collection.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Laws such as the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) and Gramm Leach Bliley Act can regulate companies but it excludes AI.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] There are state legislatures being enacted.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The state of Utah in the United States passed the Artificial Intelligence Policy Act in March of 2024.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The White House Office of Science and Technology Policy created the "Blueprint for an AI Bill of Rights" in 2022 which explained frameworks for data privacy and AI and having AI systems collect user consent prior to using their data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Many researchers have created additional frameworks to address AI and data privacy including data minimization requirements, auditing of AI, and giving users an option to opt out of data collection when using AI.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] As location tracking capabilities of mobile devices are advancing (location-based services), problems related to user privacy arise.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Location data is among the most sensitive data currently being collected.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] A list of potentially sensitive professional and personal information that could be inferred about an individual knowing only their mobility trace was published in 2009 by the Electronic Frontier Foundation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] These include the movements of a competitor sales force, attendance of a particular church or an individual's presence in a motel, or at an abortion clinic.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] A recent MIT study by de Montjoye et al. showed that four spatio-temporal points, approximate places and times, are enough to uniquely identify 95% of 1.5 million people in a mobility database.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The study further shows that these constraints hold even when the resolution of the dataset is low.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Therefore, even coarse or blurred datasets provide little anonymity to the person.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] People may not wish for their medical records to be revealed to others due to the confidentiality and sensitivity of what the information could reveal about their health.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] For example, they might be concerned that it might affect their insurance coverage or employment.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Or, it may be because they would not wish for others to know about any medical or psychological conditions or treatments that would bring embarrassment upon themselves.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Revealing medical data could also reveal other details about one's personal life.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Physicians and psychiatrists in many cultures and countries have standards for doctor–patient relationships, which include maintaining confidentiality.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In some cases, the physician–patient privilege is legally protected.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] These practices are in place to protect the dignity of patients, and to ensure that patients feel free to reveal complete and accurate information required for them to receive the correct treatment.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] To view the United States' laws on governing privacy of private health information, see HIPAA and the HITECH Act.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The Australian law is the Privacy Act 1988 Australia as well as state-based health records legislation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Children's online privacy is subject to legal protections in many ways.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In the United States, the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act of 1998 monitors the collection of personal information of children under 13 years of age The law specifically states that website operators must receive parental consent before collecting personal data of children.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The Children's Online Privacy Protection Act of 1998 applies to websites, apps, and all internet based devices that are geared towards children or know that they are collecting data from children under the age of thirteen.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Violating this law can result in penalties up to $43,792 per violation as it is enforced by the Federal Trade Commission.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Additionally, there are state attorneys general that enforce this law.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The Federal Trade Commission has continued to update the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act to meet the current update of emerging technology.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] There was an amendment made in 2013 that expanded the categories of personal information to include persistent identifiers, geolocation data, and any media with a child's description.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The Federal Trade Commisision opened another review of the Children Online Privacy Protection Act in 2019 as well in order to monitor new technologies due to children utilizing mobile devices.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Some have noted that the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act does have its limitations.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The law at this time does not prevent children from accessing inappropriate content or lying about their age.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Moreover, there have been some doubts regarding how comprehensive the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act with educational technology.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Political privacy has been a concern since voting systems emerged in ancient times.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The secret ballot is the simplest and most widespread measure to ensure that political views are not known to anyone other than the voters themselves—it is nearly universal in modern democracy and considered to be a basic right of citizenship.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In fact, even where other rights of privacy do not exist, this type of privacy very often does.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] There are several forms of voting fraud or privacy violations possible with the use of digital voting machines.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The legal protection of the right to privacy in general – and of data privacy in particular – varies greatly around the world.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Laws and regulations related to Privacy and Data Protection are constantly changing; it is seen as important to keep abreast of any changes in the law and to continually reassess compliance with data privacy and security regulations.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Data protection laws across the globe aim to secure personal information and safeguard individual privacy in a digital era.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) sets a high benchmark, emphasizing consent, transparency, and robust accountability by imposing strict penalties.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Many countries adopt similar principles, mandating that organizations implement effective security measures, respect user rights, and notify breaches.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In regions such as North America, Asia, and Oceania, data protection frameworks vary from sector-specific regulations to comprehensive legislation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Globally, these laws balance innovation with privacy, ensuring that personal data is appropriately accessible, managed ethically while mitigating misuse and cyber threats.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The United States Department of Commerce created the International Safe Harbor Privacy Principles certification program in response to the 1995 Directive on Data Protection (Directive 95/46/EC) of the European Commission.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Both the United States and the European Union officially state that they are committed to upholding information privacy of individuals, but the former has caused friction between the two by failing to meet the standards of the EU's stricter laws on personal data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The negotiation of the Safe Harbor program was, in part, to address this long-running issue.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Directive 95/46/EC declares in Chapter IV Article 25 that personal data may only be transferred from the countries in the European Economic Area to countries which provide adequate privacy protection.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Historically, establishing adequacy required the creation of national laws broadly equivalent to those implemented by Directive 95/46/EU.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Although there are exceptions to this blanket prohibition – for example where the disclosure to a country outside the EEA is made with the consent of the relevant individual (Article 26(1)(a)) – they are limited in practical scope.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] As a result, Article 25 created a legal risk to organizations which transfer personal data from Europe to the United States.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The program regulates the exchange of passenger name record information between the EU and the US.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] According to the EU directive, personal data may only be transferred to third countries if that country provides an adequate level of protection.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Some exceptions to this rule are provided, for instance when the controller themself can guarantee that the recipient will comply with the data protection rules.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The European Commission has set up the "Working party on the Protection of Individuals with regard to the Processing of Personal Data," commonly known as the "Article 29 Working Party".
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The Working Party gives advice about the level of protection in the European Union and third countries.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The Working Party negotiated with U.S. representatives about the protection of personal data, the Safe Harbor Principles were the result.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Notwithstanding that approval, the self-assessment approach of the Safe Harbor remains controversial with a number of European privacy regulators and commentators.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The Safe Harbor program addresses this issue in the following way: rather than a blanket law imposed on all organizations in the United States, a voluntary program is enforced by the Federal Trade Commission.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] U.S. organizations which register with this program, having self-assessed their compliance with a number of standards, are "deemed adequate" for the purposes of Article 25.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Personal information can be sent to such organizations from the EEA without the sender being in breach of Article 25 or its EU national equivalents.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The Safe Harbor was approved as providing adequate protection for personal data, for the purposes of Article 25(6), by the European Commission on 26 July 2000.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Under the Safe Harbor, adoptee organizations need to carefully consider their compliance with the *onward transfer obligations*, where personal data originating in the EU is transferred to the US Safe Harbor, and then onward to a third country.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The alternative compliance approach of "binding corporate rules", recommended by many EU privacy regulators, resolves this issue.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In addition, any dispute arising in relation to the transfer of HR data to the US Safe Harbor must be heard by a panel of EU privacy regulators.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In July 2007, a new, controversial, Passenger Name Record agreement between the US and the EU was made.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] A short time afterwards, the Bush administration gave exemption for the Department of Homeland Security, for the Arrival and Departure Information System (ADIS) and for the Automated Target System from the 1974 Privacy Act.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] In February 2008, Jonathan Faull, the head of the EU's Commission of Home Affairs, complained about the US bilateral policy concerning PNR.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The US had signed in February 2008 a memorandum of understanding (MOU) with the Czech Republic in exchange of a visa waiver scheme, without concerting before with Brussels.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] The tensions between Washington and Brussels are mainly caused by a lesser level of data protection in the US, especially since foreigners do not benefit from the US Privacy Act of 1974.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] Other countries approached for bilateral MOU included the United Kingdom, Estonia, Germany and Greece.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] There are techniques to improve privacy, privacy-enhancing technologies, and privacy software tools.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] People building and updating systems can use privacy by design and privacy engineering strategies and techniques.
[src:hipaa-compliance/information-privacy] For example, by converting data into a non-readable format, encryption prevents unauthorized access.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Most developed countries including Australia, Canada, Turkey, the United Kingdom, the United States, New Zealand, and the Netherlands have enacted laws protecting people's medical health privacy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] However, many of these health-securing privacy laws have proven less effective in practice than in theory.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In 1996, the United States passed the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) which aimed to increase privacy precautions within medical institutions.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The history of medical privacy traces back to the Hippocratic Oath, which mandates the secrecy of information obtained while helping a patient.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Before the technological boom, medical institutions relied on the paper medium to file individual medical data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Nowadays, more and more information is stored within electronic databases.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Research indicates that storing information on paper is safer because it is more difficult to physically steal, whereas digital records are vulnerable to hacker access.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In the early 1990s, to address healthcare privacy issues, researchers explored using credit cards and smart cards to enable secure access to medical information, aiming to mitigate fears of data theft.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The "smart" card allowed the storage and processing of information to be stored in a singular microchip, yet people were fearful of having so much information stored in a single spot that could easily be accessed.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] This "smart" card included an individual's social security number as an important piece of identification that can lead to identity theft if databases are breached.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Additionally, there was the fear that people would target these medical cards because they have information that can be of value to many different third parties, including employers, pharmaceutical companies, drug marketers, and insurance reviewers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In response to the lack of medical privacy, there was a movement to create better medical privacy protection, but nothing has been officially passed.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The Medical Information Bureau was thus created to prevent insurance fraud, yet it has since become a significant source of medical information for over 750 life insurance companies; thus, it is very dangerous as it is a target of privacy breaches.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Although the electronic filing system of medical information has increased efficiency and administration costs have been reduced, there are negative aspects to consider.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The electronic filing system allows for individual information to be more susceptible to outsiders; even though their information is stored on a singular card.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Therefore, the medical card serves as a false sense of security as it does not protect their information completely.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] With the technological boom, there has been an expansion of the record filing system and many hospitals have therefore adopted new PCMS.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] PCMS store large amounts of medical records, and hold the personal data of many individuals.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] These have become critical to the efficiency of storing medical information because of the high volumes of paperwork, the ability to quickly share information between medical institutions, and the increased mandatory reporting to the government.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] PCMS have ultimately increased the productivity of data record utilization and have created a large dependence on technology within the medical field.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] It has also led to social and ethical issues because basic human rights are considered to be violated by the PCMS, since hospitals and health information services are now more likely to share information with third-party companies.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Thus, there needs to be a reformation to specify which hospital personnel have the access to medical records.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Additionally, it is used to ensure that a person's identity is kept confidential for research or statistical purposes and to understand the process to make individuals aware that their health information is being used.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Thus, a balance between privacy and confidentiality must be kept in order to limit the amount of information disclosed and protect patients' rights by safeguarding sensitive information from third parties.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Electronic medical records are a more efficient way of storing medical information, yet there are many negative aspects of this type of filing system as well.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Hospitals are willing to adopt this type of filing system only if they are able to ensure that the private information of their patients is sufficiently protected.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Researchers have found that U.S. state legislation and regulation of medical privacy laws reduce the number of hospitals that adopt EMR by more than 24%.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] This is due to decreasing positive network externalities that are created by additional state protections.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] With increases in restrictions against the diffusion of medical information, hospitals have neglected to adopt the new EMRs because privacy laws restrict health information exchanges.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] With decreasing numbers of medical institutions adopting the EMR filing system, the U.S. government's plan of a national health network has not been fully recognized.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The national network will ultimately cost US$156 billion in investments, yet in order for this to happen, the U.S. government needs to place a higher emphasis on protecting individual privacy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Many politicians and business leaders find that EMRs allow for more efficiency in both time and money, yet they neglect to address the decreasing privacy protections, demonstrating the significant trade-off between EMRs and individual privacy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The three goals of information security, including electronic information security, are confidentiality, integrity, and availability.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Organizations are attempting to meet these goals, referred to as the C.I.A.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In a 2004 editorial in the *Washington Post*, U.S.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Senators Bill Frist and Hillary Clinton supported this observation, stating "[patients] need...information, including access to their own health records...
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] At the same time, we must ensure the privacy of the systems, or they will undermine the trust they are designed to create".
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] A 2005 report by the California Health Care Foundation found that "67 percent of national respondents felt 'somewhat' or 'very concerned' about the privacy of their personal medical records".
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The importance of privacy in electronic health records became prominent with the passage of the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act (ARRA) in 2009.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Providing patient access to EHRs is strictly mandated by HIPAA's Privacy Rule.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] One study found that each year there are an estimated 25 million compelled authorizations for the release of personal health records. .
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Researchers, however, have found new security threats open up as a result.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Some of these security and privacy threats include hackers, viruses, worms, and the unintended consequences of the speed at which patients are expected to have their records disclosed while frequently containing sensitive terms that carry the risk of accidental disclosure.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] These privacy threats are made more prominent by the emergence of "cloud computing", which is the use of shared computer processing power.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Health care organizations are increasingly using cloud computing as a way to handle large amounts of data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] This type of data storage, however, is susceptible to natural disasters, cybercrime and technological terrorism, and hardware failure.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Health information breaches accounted for the 39 percent of all breaches in 2015.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] IT Security costs and implementations are needed to protect health institutions against security and data breaches.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Although privacy issues with the health screening is a great concern among individuals and organizations, there has been little focus on the amount of work being done within the law to maintain the privacy expectation that people desire.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Many of these issues lie within the abstractness of the term "privacy" as there are many different interpretations of the term, especially in the context of the law.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Prior to 1994, there had been no cases regarding screening practices and the implications towards an individual's medical privacy, unless it was regarding HIV and drug testing.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Within *Glover v Eastern Nebraska Community Office of Retardation*, an employee sued her employer against violating her 4th amendment rights because of unnecessary HIV testing.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The court ruled in favor of the employee and argued that it was unreasonable search to have it tested.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] However, this was only one of the few precedents that people have to use.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] With more precedents, the relationships between employees and employers will be better defined.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Yet with more requirements, testing among patients will lead to additional standards for meeting health care standards.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] One of the main dangers to an individual's privacy are private corporations because of the profits they can receive from selling seemingly private information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Privacy merchants are made up of two groups - one that tries to collect people's personal information while the other focuses on using client's information to market company products.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Subsequently, privacy merchants purchase information from other companies, such as health insurance companies, if there is not sufficient information from their own research.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Privacy merchants target health insurance companies because, nowadays, they collect huge amounts of personal information and keep them in large databases.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] They often require patients to provide more information that is needed for purposes other than that of doctors and other medical workers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Additionally, people's information can be linked to other information outside of the medical field.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] For example, many employers use insurance information and medical records as an indicator of work ability and ethic.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The selling of privacy information can also lead employers to make much money; however, this happens to many people without their consent or knowledge.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Within the United States, in order to define clear privacy laws regarding medical privacy, Title 17 thoroughly explains the ownership of one's data and adjusted the law so that people have more control over their own property.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The Privacy Act of 1974 offers more restrictions regarding what corporations can access outside of an individual's consent.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] States have created additional supplements to medical privacy laws.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] With HIPAA, many individuals were pleased to see the federal government take action in protecting the medical information of individuals.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Yet when people looked into it, there was proof that the government was still protecting the rights of corporations.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Many rules were seen as more of suggestions and the punishment for compromising the privacy of its patients were minimal.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Even if release of medical information requires consent, blank authorizations can be allowed and will not ask for individuals for additional consent later on.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Previous controversies, such as Google's "Project Nightingale" in 2019 have demonstrated potential holes in regulations of patient data and medical information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Project Nightingale, a joint effort between Google and the healthcare network Ascension, saw to the selling of millions of patients' identifiable medical information without their consent.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Though Google claimed that their process was legal in obtaining the information, there was concern between researchers on this claim.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] With the lack of help from the Department of Health and Human Services there is a conflict of interest that has been made clear.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Some wish to place individual betterment as more important, while others focus more on external benefits from outside sources.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The issues that occur when there are problems between the two groups are also not adequately solved which leads to controversial laws and effects.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Individual interests take precedence over the benefits of society as a whole and are often viewed as selfish and for the gain of capital value.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] If the government does not make any more future changes to the current legislation, countless organizations and people will have access to individual medical information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In 1999, the Gramm-Leach-Billey Act (GLBA) addressed the insurance privacy debate regarding medical privacy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Yet, there were many issues with the implementation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] One issue was that there were inconsistent regulation requirements within the different states due to preexisting laws.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Secondly, it was difficult to combine the pre-existing laws with the new framework.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] And thirdly, in order for the federal government to implement these new rules, they needed state legislature to pass it.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] GLBA aimed to regulate financial institutions so that corporations could not affect people's insurance.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Because of the difficulty of the implementation of the GLBA, state legislatures are able to interpret the laws themselves and create initiatives to protect the medical privacy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] When states are creating their own independent legislature, they create standards that understand the impact of the legislation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] If they stray from the standard laws, they must be valid and fair.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The new legislation must protect the rights of businesses and allow them to continue to function despite federally regulated competition.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Patients gain benefits from these new services and standards through the flow of information that is considerate with medical privacy expectations.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] These regulations should focus more on the consumer versus the benefits and political exploitation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Many times, regulations are for the personal gain of the corporation, therefore, state legislatures be wary of this and try to prevent it to the best of their abilities.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Medical privacy is not a new issue within the insurance industry, yet the problems regarding exploitation continue to reoccur; there is more focus on taking advantage of the business environment for personal gain.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Bush passed additional regulations to HIPAA in order to better protect the privacy of individual medical information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] These new regulations were supposed to safeguard health information privacy by creating extensive solutions for the privacy of patients.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The new regulation goals included being notified once an individual's information is inspected, amend any medical records, and request communication opportunities to discuss information disclosure.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] However, there are exceptions to when the disclosure of PHI can be inspected.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] This includes specific conditions among law enforcement, judicial and administrative proceedings, parents, significant others, public health, health research, and commercial marketing.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] These aspects of lack of privacy have caused an alarming number of gaps within privacy measures.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Ultimately, there is still an issue on how to ensure privacy securities; in response, the government has created new regulations that makes trade offs between an individual's privacy and public benefit.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] These new regulations, however, still cover individually identifiable health information - any data that contains information unique to an individual.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] However, non-identifiable data is not covered as the government claims it will cause minimal damage to a person's privacy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] It also covers all health care organizations and covers businesses as well.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Additionally, under new HIPAA additions, the state legislation is more protective than national laws because it created more obligations for organizations to follow.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Ultimately, the new rules called for expansive requirements that created better safety measures for individuals.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Yet, there are still ways that businesses and healthcare organizations can be exempt from disclosure rules for all individuals.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Thus, the HHS needs to find more ways to balance personal and public trade offs within medical laws.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] This creates a need for extra government intervention to enforce legislation and new standards to decrease the number of threats against an individual's privacy of health data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The COVID-19 pandemic led to a global effort to use technologies, like contact tracing, to reduce the spread of the disease.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Contact tracing involves notifying people that they have been in contact with an individual who has tested positive for the virus.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] This led to the general public being concerned about the privacy risks of this technology.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In response, in April 2020 Apple and Google created a contact tracing API.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Patients want to be able to share medical information with their physicians, yet they worry about potential privacy breaches that can occur when they release financial and confidential medical information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In order to ensure better protection, the government has created frameworks for keeping information confidential - this includes being transparent about procedures, disclosure and protection of information, and monitoring of these new rules to ensure that people's information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Recently physicians and patients have started to use email as an additional communication tool for treatment and medical interactions.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] This way of communication is not "new", but its effects on doctor patient relationships has created new questions regarding legal, moral, and financial problems.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The American Medical Informatics Association has characterized medical emails as way to communicate "medical advice, treatment, and information exchanged professionally"; yet, the "spontaneity, permanence, and information power characterizing" role is significant because of its unknown affects.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] However, the use of emails allows for increased access, immediate aid, and increased interactions between patients and doctors.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] There are many benefits and negative aspects of using emails; doctors feel a new sense of negative responsibility to respond to emails outside of the office, but also find benefits with facilitating rapid responses to patient's questions.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Additionally, the use of email between physicians and their patients will continue to grow because of the increasing use of the Internet.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] With the Internet, patients are able to ask for medical advice and treatment, yet issues regarding confidentiality and legal issues come up.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Ultimately, emails between a physician and patient are supposed to be used as a supplement for face to face interactions, not for casual messages.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] If used properly, physicians could use emails as a way to supplement interactions and provide more medical aid to those who need it immediately.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Although many people believe that the technological changes are the reason for fear of sharing medical privacy, there is a theory that states that institutional ideals between doctors and their patients have created the fear of sharing medical privacy information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Although levels of confidentiality are changing, individuals often feel the need to share more information with their doctors in order to get diagnosed correctly.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Because of this, people are concerned with how much information their physicians have.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] This information could be transferred to other third-party companies.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] However, there is a call for smaller emphasis on sharing and confidentiality in order to rid patients from their fears of information breaching.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] There is a common belief that the confidentiality of one's information also only protects the doctors and not the patients, therefore there is a negative stigma towards revealing too much information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Thus it causes patients to not share vital information relevant to their illnesses.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] On July 1, 2012, the Australian Government launched the Personally Controlled Electronic Health Record (PCEHR) (eHealth) system.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The full implementation incorporates an electronic summary prepared by nominated healthcare providers along with consumer-provided notes.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Further, the summary includes information on the individual's allergies, adverse reactions, medications, immunizations, diagnoses, and treatments.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The consumer notes operate as a personal medical diary that only the individual can view and edit.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The opt-in system gives people the option to choose whether to register for the eHealth record or not.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] As of January 2016, the Commonwealth Department of Health changed the name PCEHR to My Health Record.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The Personally Controlled Electronic Health Records Act 2012 and Privacy Act 1988 governs how eHealth record information is managed and protected.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The PCEHR System Operator abides by the Information Privacy Principles in the Privacy Act 1988 (Commonwealth) as well as any applicable State or Territory privacy laws.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] A Privacy Statement sets out the application of the collection of personal information by the System Operator.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The statement includes an explanation of the types of personal information collected, what the information is used for, and how the information is stored.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The statement covers measures in place to protect personal information from misuse, loss, unauthorized access, modification, and disclosure.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Security measures include audit trails so that patients can see who has accessed their medical records along with the time the records were accessed.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Other measures include the use of encryption as well as secure logins and passwords.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Patient records are identified using an Individual Health Identifier (IHI), assigned by Medicare, the IHI service provider.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] A 2012 nationwide survey in Australia assessed privacy concerns on patients' health care decisions, which could impact patient care.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Results listed that 49.1% of Australian patients stated they have withheld or would withhold information from their health care provider based on privacy concerns.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] One concern is that personal control of the eHealth record via consent does not guarantee the protection of privacy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] It is argued that a narrow definition, 'permission' or 'agreement', does not provide protection for privacy and is not well represented in Australian legislation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The PCEHR allows clinicians to assume consent by consumer participation in the system; however, the needs of the consumer may not be met.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Critics argue that the broader definition of 'informed consent' is required, as it encompasses the provision of relevant information by the healthcare practitioner, and understanding of that information by the patient.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Data from the PCEHR is to be predominantly used in patient healthcare, but other uses are possible, for policy, research, audit and public health purposes.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The concern is that in the case of research, what is allowed goes beyond existing privacy legislation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The involvement of pharmaceutical companies is viewed as potentially problematic.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] If they are perceived by the public to be more concerned with profit than public health, public acceptance of their use of PCEHRs could be challenged.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Also perceived as problematic, is the potential for parties other than health care practitioners, such as insurance companies, employers, police or the government, to use information in a way which could result in discrimination or disadvantage.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Information 'leakage' is seen as having the potential to discourage both patient and clinician from participating in the system.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Critics argue the PCEHR initiative can only work, if a safe, effective continuum of care within a trusting patient/clinician relationship is established.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] If patients lose trust in the confidentiality of their eHealth information, they may withhold sensitive information from their health care providers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Clinicians may be reluctant to participate in a system where they are uncertain about the completeness of the information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Security experts have questioned the registration process, where those registering only have to provide a Medicare card number, and names and birth dates of family members to verify their identity.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Concerns have also been raised by some stakeholders, about the inherent complexities of the limited access features.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] They warn that access to PCEHR record content, may involve transfer of information to a local system, where PCEHR access controls would no longer apply.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The privacy of patient information is protected at both the federal level and provincial level in Canada.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The health information legislation established the rules that must be followed for the collection, use, disclosure and protection of health information by healthcare workers known as "custodians".
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] These custodians have been defined to include almost all healthcare professionals (including all physicians, nurses, chiropractors, operators of ambulances and operators of nursing homes).
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In addition to the regulatory bodies of specific healthcare workers, the provincial privacy commissions are central to the protection of patient information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The privacy of patient information is guaranteed by articles 78 and 100 of legal code 5510.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] On the other hand, the Social Security Institution (SGK), which regulates and administers state-sponsored social security / insurance benefits, sells patient information after allegedly anonymizing the data, confirmed on October 25, 2014.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The National Health Service is increasingly using electronic health records, but until recently, the records held by individual NHS organisations, such as General Practitioners, NHS Trusts, dentists and pharmacies, were not linked.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Each organization was responsible for the protection of patient data it collected.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The care. data programme, which proposed to extract anonymised data from GP surgeries into a central database, aroused considerable opposition.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In 2003, the NHS made moves to create a centralized electronic registry of medical records.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The system is protected by the UK's Government Gateway, which was built by Microsoft.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] This program is known as the Electronic Records Development and the Implementation Programme (ERDIP).
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The NHS National Program for IT was criticized for its lack of security and lack of patient privacy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] It was one of the projects that caused the Information Commissioner to warn about the danger of the country "sleepwalking" into a surveillance society.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Pressure groups opposed to ID cards also campaigned against the centralized registry.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Newspapers feature stories about lost computers and memory sticks but a more common and longstanding problem is about staff accessing records that they have no right to see.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] It has always been possible for staff to look at paper records, and in most cases, there is no track of record.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Therefore, electronic records make it possible to keep track of who has accessed which records.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] NHS Wales has created the National Intelligent Integrated Audit System which provides "a range of automatically generated reports, designed to meet the needs of our local health boards and trusts, instantly identifying any potential issues when access has not been legitimate".
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Maxwell Stanley Consulting will use a system called Patient Data Protect (powered by VigilancePro) which can spot patterns – such as whether someone is accessing data about their relatives or colleagues.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Since 1974, numerous federal laws have been passed in the United States to specify the privacy rights and protections of patients, physicians, and other covered entities to medical data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Many states have passed its own laws to try and better protect the medical privacy of their citizens.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] An important national law regarding medical privacy is the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996 (HIPAA), yet there are many controversies regarding the protection rights of the law.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The most comprehensive law passed is the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996 (HIPAA), which was later revised after the Final Omnibus Rule in 2013.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] HIPAA provides a federal minimum standard for medical privacy, sets standards for uses and disclosures of protected health information (PHI), and provides civil and criminal penalties for violations.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Prior to HIPAA, only certain groups of people were protected under medical laws such as individuals with HIV or those who received Medicare aid.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] HIPAA provides protection of health information and supplements additional state and federal laws; yet it should be understood that the law's goal is to balance public health benefits, safety, and research while protecting the medical information of individuals.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Yet many times, privacy is compromised for the benefits of the research and public health.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] According to HIPAA, the covered entities that must follow the law's set mandates are health plans, health care clearinghouses, and health care providers that electronically transmit PHI.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Business associates of these covered entities are also subject to HIPAA's rules and regulations.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In 2008, Congress passed the Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act of 2008 (GINA), which aimed to prohibit genetic discrimination for individuals seeking health insurance and employment.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The law also included a provision which mandated that genetic information held by employers be maintained in a separate file and prohibited disclosure of genetic information except in limited circumstances.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In 2013, after GINA was passed, the HIPAA Omnibus Rule amended HIPAA regulations to include genetic information in the definition of Protected Health Information (PHI).
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] This rule also expanded HIPAA by broadening the definition of business associates to include any entity that sends or accesses PHI such as health IT vendors.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) is critiqued for not providing strong medical privacy protections as it only provides regulations that disclose certain information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The government authorizes the access of an individual's health information for "treatment, payment, and health care options without patient consent".
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Additionally, HIPAA rules are very broad and do not protect an individual from unknown privacy threats.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Additionally, a patient would not be able to identify the reason for breach due to inconsistent requirements.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Because of limited confidentiality, HIPAA facilitates the sharing of medical information as there is little limitation from different organizations.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Information can easily be exchanged between medical institutions and other non-medical institutions because of the little regulation of HIPAA - some effects include job loss due to credit score sharing or loss of insurance.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Additionally, doctors are not required to keep patients information confidential because in many cases patient consent is now optional.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Patients are often unaware of the lack of privacy they have as medical processes and forms do not explicitly state the extent of how protected they are.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Physicians believe that overall, HIPAA will cause unethical and non-professional mandates that can affect a person's privacy and therefore, they in response have to provide warnings about their privacy concerns.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Because physicians are not able to ensure a person's privacy, there is a higher chance that patients will be less likely to get treatment and share what their medical concerns are.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Individuals have asked for better consent requirements by asking if physicians can warn them prior to the sharing of any personal information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Patients want to be able to share medical information with their physicians, yet they worry about potential breaches that can release financial information and other confidential information and with that fear, they are wary of who may have access.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Although there are many frameworks to ensure the protection of basic medical data, many organizations do not have these provisions in check.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] HIPAA gives a false hope to patients and physicians as they are unable to protect their own information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Patients have little rights regarding their medical privacy rights and physicians cannot guarantee those.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] HIPAA does not protect the information of individuals as the government is able to publish certain information when they find it necessary.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The government is exempted from privacy rules regarding national security.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] HIPAA additionally allows the authorization of protected health information (PHI) in order to aid in threats to public health and safety as long as it follows the good faith requirement - the idea that disclosing of information is necessary to the benefit of the public.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The Model State Emergency Powers Act (MSEHPA) gives the government the power to "suspend regulations, seize property, quarantine individuals and enforce vaccinations" and requires that healthcare providers give information regarding potential health emergencies".
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In regards to Hurricane Katrina, many people in Louisiana relied on Medicaid and their PHI was subsequently affected.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] People's medical privacy rights were soon waived in order for patient's to get the treatment they needed.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Yet, many patients were unaware that their rights had been waived.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In order to prevent the sharing of personal information in future natural disasters, a website was created in order to protect people's medical data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Ultimately, Katrina showed that the government was unprepared to face a national health scare.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Many patients mistakenly believe that HIPAA protects all health information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] HIPAA does not usually cover fitness trackers, social media sites and other health data created by the patient.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Health information can be disclosed by patients in emails, blogs, chat groups, or social media sites including those dedicated to specific illnesses, "liking" web pages about diseases, completing online health and symptom checkers, and donating to health causes.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In addition, credit card payments for physician visit co-pays, purchase of over the counter (OTC) medications, home testing products, tobacco products, and visits to alternative practitioners are also not covered by HIPAA.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] A 2015 study reported over 165,000 health apps available to consumers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Disease treatment and management account for nearly a quarter of consumer apps.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Two-thirds of the apps target fitness and wellness, and ten percent of these apps can collect data from a device or sensor.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Since the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) only regulates medical devices and most of these applications are not medical devices, they do not require FDA approval.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The data from most apps are outside HIPAA regulations because they do not share data with healthcare providers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] "Patients may mistakenly assume that mobile apps are under the scope of HIPAA since the same data, such as heart rate, may be collected by an application that is accessible to their physician and covered by HIPAA, or on a mobile app that is not accessible to the physician and not covered by HIPAA.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In 2000, there was a new surge to add new regulations to HIPAA.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The implementation of these new goals was complicated by the change in administrations (Clinton to Bush), so it was difficult for the changes to be successfully implemented.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] HIPAA, in theory, should apply to all insurance companies, services, and organizations, yet there are exceptions to who actually qualifies under these categories.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Yet, within each category, there are specific restrictions that are different in every category.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] There are no universal laws that can be easily applied that are easy for organizations can follow.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Thus, many states have neglected to implement these new policies.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Additionally, there are new patient rights that call for better protection and disclosure of health information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] However, like the new rules regarding insurance companies, the enforcement of the legislation is limited and not effective as they are too broad and complex.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Therefore, it is difficult for many organizations to ensure the privacy of these people.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Enforcing these new requirements also causes companies to spend many resources that they are not willing to use and enforce, which ultimately leads to further problems regarding the invasion of an individual's medical privacy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The Oregon Genetic Privacy Act (GPA) states that "an individual's genetic information is the property of the individual".
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The idea of an individual's DNA being compared to property occurred when research caused an individual's privacy to be threatened.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Many individuals believed that their genetic information was "more sensitive, personal, and potentially damaging than other types of medical information." Thus, people started calling for more protections.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] People started to question how their DNA would be able to stay anonymous within research studies and argued that the identity of an individual could be exposed if the research was later shared.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] As a result, there was a call for individuals to treat their DNA as property and protect it through property rights.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Therefore, individuals can control the disclosure of their information without extra questioning and research.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Many people believed that comparing one's DNA to property was inappropriate, yet individuals argued that property and privacy are interconnected because they both want to protect the right to control one's body.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Many research and pharmaceutical companies showed opposition because they were worried about conflicts that might arise regarding privacy issues within their work.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Individuals, on the other hand, continued to support the act because they wanted protection over their own DNA.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] As a result, lawmakers created a compromise that included a property clause, that would give individuals protection rights, but also included provisions that would allow research to be done without much consent, limiting the benefits of the provisions.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Afterwards, a committee was created to study the effects of the act and how it affected the way it was analyzed and stored.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] They found that the act benefited many individuals who did not want their privacy being shared with others and therefore the law was officially implemented in 2001.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In order to solve HIPAA issues within Connecticut, state legislatures tried to create better provisions to protect the people living within the state.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] One of the issues that Connecticut tried to solve were issues with consent.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Within the consent clause, health plans and health care clearinghouses do not need to receive consent from individuals because of a general provider consent form with gives healthcare providers permission to disclose all medical information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The patient thus does not get notification when their information is being shared afterwards.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Connecticut, like many other states, tried to protect individual's information from disclosure of information through additional clauses that would protect them from businesses initiatives.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In order to do so, Connecticut legislature passed the Connecticut Insurance Information and Privacy Protect Act, which provides additional protections of individual medical information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] If third parties neglect to follow this law, they will be fined, may face jail time, and may have their licenses suspended.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Yet, even in these additional provisions, there were many holes within this legislation that allowed for businesses agreements to be denied and subsequently, information was compromised.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Connecticut is still working to shift its divergent purposes to creating more stringent requirements that create better protections through clear provisions of certain policies.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In California, the Confidentiality of Medical Information Act (CMIA), provides more stringent protections than the federal statutes.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] HIPAA expressly provides that more stringent state laws like CMIA, will override HIPAA's requirements and penalties.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] More specifically, CMIA prohibits providers, contractors and health care service plans from disclosing PHI without prior authorization.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] These medical privacy laws also set a higher standard for health IT vendors or vendors of an individual's personal health record (PHR) by applying such statutes to vendors, even if they are not business associates of a covered entity.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] CMIA also outlines penalties for violating the law.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] These penalties range from liability to the patient (compensatory damages, punitive damages, attorneys' fees, costs of litigation) to civil and even criminal liability.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Likewise, California's Insurance Information and Privacy Protection Act (IIPPA) protects against unauthorized disclosure of PHI by prohibiting unapproved information sharing for information collected from insurance applications and claims resolution.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In New Zealand, the Health Information Privacy Code (1994) sets specific rules for agencies in the health sector to better ensure the protection of individual privacy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The code addresses the health information collected, used, held and disclosed by health agencies.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] For the health sector, the code takes the place of the information privacy principles.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] The introduction of a nationwide system for the exchange of medical information and access to electronic patient records led to much discussion in the Netherlands.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In the course of having or being part of a medical practice, doctors may obtain information that they wish to share with the medical or research community.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] If this information is shared or published, the privacy of the patients must be respected.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] Likewise, participants in medical research that are outside the realm of direct patient care have a right to privacy as well.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] While medical privacy remains an important right, it is also crucial to balance privacy with innovation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] By limiting patient data in response to privacy violations, it potentially hinders data-driven innovation in medicine.
[src:hipaa-compliance/medical-privacy] In addition, keeping data secret for a competitive advantage also poses multiple concerns, potentially slowing advances in medical testing (e.g.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The abbreviation PII is widely used in the United States, but the phrase it abbreviates has four common variants based on *personal* or *personally*, and *identifiable* or *identifying*.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Not all are equivalent, and for legal purposes the effective definitions vary depending on the jurisdiction and the purposes for which the term is being used.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Under European Union and United Kingdom data protection regimes, which centre primarily on the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), the term "personal data" is significantly broader, and determines the scope of the regulatory regime.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Personal data is defined under the GDPR as "any information which [is] related to an identified or identifiable natural person".
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The IP address of an Internet subscriber may be classed as personal data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The concept of PII has become prevalent as information technology and the Internet have made it easier to collect PII leading to a profitable market in collecting and reselling PII.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] PII can also be exploited by criminals to stalk or steal the identity of a person, or to aid in the planning of criminal acts.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] As a response to these threats, many website privacy policies specifically address the gathering of PII, and lawmakers such as the European Parliament have enacted a series of legislative acts such as the GDPR to limit the distribution and accessibility of PII.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Serious confusion arises around whether PII means information which is identifiable (that is, can be associated with a person) or identifying (that is, associated uniquely with a person, such that the PII *identifies* them).
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] In prescriptive data privacy regimes such as the US federal Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA), PII items have been specifically defined.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] In broader data protection regimes such as the GDPR, personal data is defined in a non-prescriptive principles-based way.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Information that might not count as PII under HIPAA can be personal data for the purposes of GDPR.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] For this reason, "PII" is typically deprecated internationally.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] In the EU rules, there has been a more specific notion that the data subject can potentially be identified through additional processing of other attributes—quasi- or pseudo-identifiers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] A simple example of this distinction: the color name "red" by itself is *not* personal data, but that same value stored as part of a person's record as their "favorite color" *is* personal data; it is the connection to the person that makes it personal data, not (as in PII) the value itself.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The concept of information combination given in the SB1386 definition is key to correctly distinguishing PII, as defined by OMB, from "personal information", as defined by SB1386.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Information, such as a name, that lacks context cannot be said to be SB1386 "personal information", but it must be said to be PII as defined by OMB.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] For example, the name "John Smith" has no meaning in the current context and is therefore not SB1386 "personal information", but it is PII.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] A Social Security Number (SSN) without a name or some other associated identity or context information is not SB1386 "personal information", but it is PII.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] For example, the SSN 078-05-1120 by itself is PII, but it is not SB1386 "personal information".
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] However the combination of a valid name with the correct SSN is SB1386 "personal information".
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The combination of a name with a context may also be considered PII; for example, if a person's name is on a list of patients for an HIV clinic.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] However, it is not necessary for the name to be combined with a context in order for it to be PII.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The reason for this distinction is that bits of information such as names, although they may not be sufficient by themselves to make an identification, may later be combined with other information to identify persons and expose them to harm.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The scope of the term "sensitive personal data" varies by jurisdiction.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] In the UK, personal health data is treated as "sensitive" and in need of additional data protection measures.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] According to the OMB, in the United States it is not always the case that PII is "sensitive", and context may be taken into account in deciding whether certain PII is or is not sensitive.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] When a person wishes to remain anonymous, descriptions of them will often employ several of the above, such as "a 34-year-old white male who works at Target".
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Information can still be *private*, in the sense that a person may not wish for it to become publicly known, without being personally identifiable.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Moreover, sometimes multiple pieces of information, none sufficient by itself to uniquely identify an individual, may uniquely identify a person when combined; this is one reason that multiple pieces of evidence are usually presented at criminal trials.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] It has been shown that, in 1990, 87% of the population of the United States could be uniquely identified by gender, ZIP code, and full date of birth.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] In hacker and Internet slang, the practice of finding and releasing such information is called "doxing".
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] It is sometimes used to deter collaboration with law enforcement.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] On occasion, the doxing can trigger an arrest, particularly if law enforcement agencies suspect that the "doxed" individual may panic and disappear.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] It appears that this definition is significantly broader than the Californian example given above, and thus that Australian privacy law may cover a broader category of data and information than in some US law.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The term "PII" is not used in Australian privacy law.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] European Union data protection law does not use the concept of personally identifiable information, and its scope is instead determined by the non-synonymous, wider concept of "personal data".
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Further examples can be found on the EU privacy website.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] On 1 June 2023, the Hong Kong Office of the Privacy Commissioner for Personal Data published an investigation report on a data breach involving the unauthorised access of a credit reference database platform.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The Report highlights the need for organizations to take adequate steps to protect personal data as the mere imposition of contractual obligations and policies is insufficient if such obligations and policies are not effective or are not enforced.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The Report also clarifies that credit data is a form of "sensitive" personal data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The twelve Information Privacy Principles of the Privacy Act 1993 apply.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] New Zealand enacted the Privacy Act in 2020 to promote and protect individual privacy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The Federal Act on Data Protection of 19 June 1992 (in force since 1993) has set up a protection of privacy by prohibiting virtually any processing of personal data which is not expressly authorized by the data subjects.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The protection is subject to the authority of the Federal Data Protection and Information Commissioner.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Additionally, any person may ask in writing a company managing data files to correct or delete any personal data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The company must respond within thirty days.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] One of the primary focuses of the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) is to protect a patient's Protected Health Information (PHI), which is similar to PII.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Senate proposed the Privacy Act of 2005, which attempted to strictly limit the display, purchase, or sale of PII without the person's consent.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Similarly, the (proposed) Anti-Phishing Act of 2005 attempted to prevent the acquiring of PII through phishing.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] U.S. lawmakers have paid special attention to the social security number because it can be easily used to commit identity theft.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The (proposed) Social Security Number Protection Act of 2005 and (proposed) Identity Theft Prevention Act of 2005 each sought to limit the distribution of an individual's social security number.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Additional U.S.-specific personally identifiable information includes, but is not limited to, I-94 records, Medicaid ID numbers, and Internal Revenue Service (I.R.S.) documentation.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Exclusivity of personally identifiable information affiliated with the U.S. highlights national data security concerns and the influence of personally identifiable information in U.S. federal data management systems.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) is a physical sciences laboratory, and a non-regulatory agency of the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Its mission is to promote innovation and industrial competitiveness.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The following are less often used to distinguish individual identity, because they are traits shared by many people.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] However, they are potentially PII, because they may be combined with other personal information to identify an individual.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] In forensics, particularly the identification and prosecution of criminals, personally identifiable information is critical in establishing evidence in criminal procedure.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Personal data is a key component of online identity and can be exploited by individuals.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] For instance, data can be altered and used to create fake documents, hijack mail boxes and phone calls or harass people, as occurred in 2019 to a customer of the EE mobile phone operator in the UK.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Another category can be referred to as financial identity theft, which usually entails bank account and credit card information being stolen, and then being used or sold.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Personal data can also be used to create fake online identities, including fake accounts and profiles (which can be referred as identity cloning or identity fraud) for celebrities to gather data from other users more easily.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Even individuals can be concerned, especially for personal purposes (this is more widely known as sockpuppetry).
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The most critical information, such as one's password, date of birth, ID documents or social security number, can be used to log in to different websites (e.g. password reuse and account verification) to gather more information and access more content.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Also, several agencies ask for discretion on subjects related to their work, for the safety of their employees.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] For this reason, the United States Department of Defense (DoD) has strict policies controlling release of personally identifiable information of DoD personnel.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Many intelligence agencies have similar policies, sometimes to the point where employees do not disclose to their friends that they work for the agency.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Similar identity protection concerns exist for witness protection programs, women's shelters, and victims of domestic violence and other threats.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Personal information removal services work by identifying and requesting data brokers to delete the personal information of their clients.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] This process can be manual or fully automated, but it is nevertheless complex because it involves dealing with numerous data brokers, each with different policies and procedures for data removal.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Companies offering personal information removal also face some issues.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] They struggle to ensure comprehensive data removal as new data brokers emerge and existing ones don’t always comply with removal requests.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Most of them are also limited to certain regions or countries.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] During the second half of the 20th century, the digital revolution introduced "privacy economics", or the trade of personal data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The value of data can change over time and over different contexts.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Disclosing data can reverse information asymmetry, though the costs of doing so can be unclear.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] In relation to companies, consumers often have "imperfect information regarding when their data is collected, with what purposes, and with what consequences".
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] In the mid-1990s, Varian retook the Chicago Boys approach and added a new externality, stating that the consumer would not always have perfect information on how their own data would be used.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Laudon developed a model in which individuals own their data and have the ability to sell it as a product.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] He believed that such a system should not be regulated, to create a free market.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] In the 2000s, researchers worked on price discrimination (Taylor, 2004), two-sided markets (Cornière, 2011) and marketing strategies (Anderson and de Palma, 2012).
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The theories became complex, and showed that the impact of privacy on the economy highly depended on the context.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Sources, usually Internet-based since the 1990s, may include census and electoral roll records, social networking sites, court reports and purchase histories.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] The information from data brokers may be used in background checks used by employers and housing.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] There are varying regulations around the world limiting the collection of information on individuals; privacy laws vary.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] In the United States there is no federal regulation protection for the consumer from data brokers, although some states have begun enacting laws individually.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] In the European Union, GDPR serves to regulate data brokers' operations.
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Some data brokers report to have large numbers of population data or "data attributes".
[src:hipaa-compliance/personal-data] Acxiom purports to have data from 2.5 billion different people.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] PHI is sought out in datasets for de-identification before researchers share the dataset publicly.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Researchers remove individually and identifiable PHI from a dataset to preserve privacy for research participants.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] There are many forms of PHI, with the most common being physical storage in the form of paper-based personal health records.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Other types of PHI include electronic health records, wearable technology, and mobile applications.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] In recent years, there has been a growing number of concerns regarding the safety and privacy of PHI.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] All geographical identifiers smaller than a state, except for the initial three digits of a zip code if, according to the current publicly available data from the U.S.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Anonymization is a process in which PHI elements are eliminated or manipulated with the purpose of hindering the possibility of going back to the original data set.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] This involves removing all identifying data to create unlinkable data.De-identification under the privacy rule occurs when data has been stripped of common identifiers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] De-identified data is coded, with a link to the original, fully identified data set kept by an honest broker.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Links exist in coded de-identified data making the data considered indirectly identifiable and not anonymized.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Coded de-identified data is not protected by the HIPAA Privacy Rule, but is protected under the Common Rule.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] The purpose of de-identification and anonymization is to use health care data in larger increments, for research purposes.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Universities, government agencies, and private health care entities use such data for research, development and marketing purposes.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] U.S. law governing PHI applies to data collected in the course of providing and paying for health care.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Privacy and security regulations govern how healthcare professionals, hospitals, health insurers, and other Covered Entities use and protect the data they collect.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] It is important to understand that the source of the data is as relevant as the data itself when determining if information is PHI under U.S. law.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] For example, sharing information about someone on the street with an obvious medical condition such as an amputation is not restricted by U.S. law.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] However, obtaining information about the amputation exclusively from a protected source, such as from an electronic medical record, would breach HIPAA regulations.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Covered entities often use third parties to provide certain health and business services.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] If they need to share PHI with those third parties, it is the responsibility of the covered entity to put in place a Business Associate Agreement that holds the third party to the same standards of privacy and confidentiality as the Covered Entity.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Protected health information can be stored in many different forms.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] According to HIPAA, there are many requirements and limitations regarding how PHI can be stored.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Until recently, physical storage has been the most common method of storing PHI.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Physical safeguards for PHI include storing paper records in locked cabinets and enabling a control over the records.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] A security authority, PIN pad, or identification card could all be necessary to access physical storage of PHI.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Much of PHI is stored in electronic health records (EHR).
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Cloud computing and other services allow healthcare providers to store vast amounts of data for easy access.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] For example, Kaiser Permanente has over 9 million members and stores anywhere from 25 to 44 petabytes.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] In Australia, over 90% of healthcare institutions have implemented EHRs, in an attempt to improve efficiency.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] E-health architecture types can either be public, private, hybrid, or community, depending on the data stored.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Healthcare providers will often store their data on a vast network of remote servers, proving susceptible to privacy breaches.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] According to a study, the US could save $81 billion annually from switching to a universal electronic health record (EHR).
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] In PHI, wearable technology often comes in the form of smartwatches, ECG monitors, blood pressure monitors, and biosensors.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Wearable technology has faced rapid growth with 102.4 million units shipped in 2016, up 25% from the 81.9 million units shipped in 2015.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] According to Insider Intelligence research, the number of health and fitness app users will remain over 84 million through 2022.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Health and fitness tracking capabilities are a target for companies producing wearable technology.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Privacy concerns for consumers arise when these technology companies are not considered covered entities or business associates under HIPAA or where the health information collected is not PHI.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Mobile applications have been proven essential, especially for the elderly or disabled.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] The adoption of mobile healthcare is said to be attractive due to factors like patient behavior, subjective norm, personal innovativeness, perceived behavioral control, and behavioral intention.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] The legitimacy of certain mobile applications that store PHI can be determined by the user reviews on the application.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] In a study conducted by researchers, 14 patients were asked for their opinions on privacy concerns and healthcare perceptions.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Researchers found that all participants agreed on the importance of healthcare privacy.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Participants demonstrated a vague understanding of the legislated patient privacy rights.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] There were differing opinions on whose responsibility it should be to protect health information; some thought it was their own responsibility, while others thought that the government was responsible.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Consent was rarely brought up within the discussion.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Because patient privacy is the reason for regulations on PHI, analyzing consumer data can be extremely difficult to come by.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Luca Bonomi and Xiaoqian Jiang determined a technique to perform temporal record linkage using non-protected health information data.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] As standard linkage processes lack the ability to incorporate the time setting, they result in being ineffective.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Bonomi and Jiang propose using the patient's non-protected health information data to determine records and establish patterns.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] This approach allows the linkage of patient records using non-PHI data, by giving doctors patterns and a better idea of important diagnoses.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] PHI is susceptible to phishing, eavesdropping, location threats, and internal attacks.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] From 2005 to 2019, the total number of individuals affected by healthcare data breaches was 249.09 million.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] According to an IBM report, the average cost of a data breach in 2019 was $3.92 million, while a healthcare industry breach usually costs $6.45 million.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] However, the average cost of a healthcare data breach (average breach size 25,575 records) in the U.S. is $15 million.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] In 2017, healthcare compliance analytics platform Protenus stated that 477 healthcare breaches were reported to the U.S.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Of these, 407 showed that 5.579 million patient records were affected.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] The 2018 Verizon Protected Health Information Data Breach Report examined 27 countries and 1368 incidents, detailing that the focus of healthcare breaches was mainly the patients, their identities, health histories, and treatment plans.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] According to HIPAA, 255.18 million people were affected from 3051 healthcare data breach incidents from 2010 to 2019.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Health-related fraud is estimated to cost the U.S. nearly $80 billion annually.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] The healthcare industry remains the most costly and targeted industry to data breaches.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Healthcare companies have been criticized for not adapting and prioritizing data security.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] One reason is due to the leeway and minimal penalties for those that fail to comply with the HIPAA Security Rule.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] There is also limited competition and a stable customer base within the healthcare industry.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Researchers are searching for more secure ways to protect PHI.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] There are ethical concerns regarding how information is treated on a daily basis by healthcare personnel.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] In 1996, the Clinton Administration passed the HIPAA Privacy Rule, limiting a physician's ability to arbitrarily disclose patients' personal medical records.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] As health artificial intelligence (AI) applications are expected to save over $150 billion in annual savings for U.S. healthcare, researchers are studying the risks of potential PHI leaks.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] Currently, 21% of U.S. consumers or 57 million people, use a quantified self health and fitness tracking application.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] In a study conducted by Nancy Brinson and Danielle Rutherford, over 90% of consumers were comfortable with the opportunity to share data with a healthcare provider.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] However, Brinson and Rutherford claim that consumers fail to make privacy a priority when they choose to share this information.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] To combat misuse of PHI on mobile healthcare platforms, Brinson and Rutherford suggest the creation of a policy rating system for consumers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] A rating system, monitored by the Federal Trade Commission would allow consumers a centralized way to evaluate data collection methods amongst mobile health providers.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] In 2019, the US Department of Health and Human Services Office for Civil Rights (OCA) promised to enforce patients' right to access under HIPAA, using the Right of Access Initiative.
[src:hipaa-compliance/protected-health-information] There have currently already been two settlements with the OCA under the Right of Access Initiative, after companies failed to give patient medical records.
